english:
  title: A Record of Traveling to Diamond Mountain
  author: Nam Hyo-on
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Diamond Mountain rises from the borders of Jurchen lands and extends southward several thousand li to the Korean coast. Among the great mountains, it appears as Five-Peak Mountain in Youngan Province, Diamond Mountain in Kangwon Province, and Jirisan in Kyongsang Province. Yet when it comes to springs and stones of surpassing beauty and wonder, Diamond Mountain stands supreme.

    The mountain bears six names. One is Kaegol, another is Maple Peak—these are regional appellations. One is Chidal and one is Diamond, both drawn from the Avatamsaka Sutra. One is City of Myriad Fragrances, drawn from the Mahayana Perfection of Wisdom Sutra. These latter names were bestowed after King Beophung of Silla.

    I humbly consider this matter: the Buddha was originally a prince of the Western Regions. His kingdom lay nine thousand li from Chang'an, separated by the distant reaches of Flowing Sand and Black Water, guarded by Dragon Heap and Onion Range—lands beyond all intercourse with the Middle Kingdom. How then could he have known of this mountain here in the East? Not merely did he know naught of this mountain, but of the Kingdom of Choson itself he must have been equally ignorant. Judging by history, in the time of King Zhao of Zhou, our nation was then the Choson of Kija, while the Buddha was born in distant Shravasti of the Western lands. In all the thousand scrolls and ten thousand fascicles of his teachings, though he spoke of infinite worlds, never once did he name the Kingdom of Choson. Clearly he knew neither this nation nor this mountain.

    Was it not rather that when the Buddha expounded his dharma, he magnified his words, claiming that in the sea there existed Diamond Mountains and various other peaks, with myriads upon myriads of Avalokiteshvara and his retinue, seeking thereby to startle simple folk—much as Zhuangzi spoke of Kunpeng in the great pool of Heaven, or told of the fairy lands of Guoshe—creating wonders in the void to astonish the vulgar? This was merely to move the ignorant masses and deceive the unlearned. Can it truly be that Diamond and Chital mountains exist so wondrously as described?

    Yet the Silla monks who followed the Buddha, in their own delusion, chose to aggrandize their own land, taking Maple Peak and naming it Diamond Mountain, fashioning images of Avalokiteshvara—thus converting falsehood into supposed fact. How could the Buddha have meant the Eastern Sea specifically? East, West, South, North—all have seas. Why then should only the Eastern Sea be called "the middle of the sea," and Maple Peak be fixed as Diamond Mountain? Moreover, though our nation lies beyond the seas from the Middle Kingdom, to the northwest our land connects by terrain to Liaodong, with only the Yalu River between us—and surely the Yalu is no sea. How greatly mistaken is the claim that our nation lies in the middle of the sea!

    Yet since the name Diamond Mountain has held for generations unnumbered, sudden change proves difficult. I too shall call it Diamond Mountain. Indeed, as a mountain, it spans the heavens north and south, towering magnificently, pressing down upon the earth's vastness. It bears thirty-six great peaks and thirteen thousand lesser peaks. One branch extends two hundred li southward, its form high and precipitous, resembling somewhat the essence of diamond. The main mountain is called Snowy Peak. To its south lies a subsidiary range. Another eastern branch forms a lesser peak called Heavenly Treasure Mountain. When heaven brings rain or snow, the mountain itself seems to weep, hence sometimes called Weeping Mountain. This extends through Yangyang and down to the seacoast where five peaks stand distinctly apart, called Naksan. A northern extension of Diamond Mountain runs over a hundred li, with one ridge called Chugji Lake. From Chugji Lake the mountains continue beyond Tongchon, scattered peaks continuing like an unbroken thread until they reach the sea, forming a place called Chorsung Pavilion.

    On the eastern side lie Tongchon, Gosong, and Kansung counties. On the western side lie Kumsung county and Hoiyang province. In all, one province, three counties, and one district are arrayed beneath these mountains.

    [The author then provides a detailed day-by-day account of his journey, beginning in the fourth month of the year of the tiger, departing from the capital and journeying through various stages, crossing rivers and mountains, until reaching the Diamond Mountain region.]

    Upon entering the mountain, I ascended through various passes and temples, observing the extraordinary formations—stone peaks like brush tips, waterfalls descending dozens of fathoms, pools of crystalline clarity. The colors shifted with the light: white stones so polished they seemed mirrors, clear waters reflecting sky. I visited numerous hermitages—Balyeon, Mahayana, Bodhisattva Cave, and many others—each with its own wonders and stories.

    Climbing to the highest viewing places, I beheld the assembled peaks: Avalokiteshvara Peak to the south, the towering Vairocana Peak dominating all others, countless lesser summits arrayed like petals around the great flower of the mountain itself. From the high viewing pavilion, the world below seemed but shadow while the true peaks revealed their majesty.

    Descending again to the eastern slopes, I traveled through the great valley where twelve waterfalls collect—sometimes plunging clear, sometimes hiding in mist, forever singing their ancient song. Along the western routes I passed through lands of apricot and azalea, where even in spring's warmth the mountain kept its chill majesty.

    Returning through valleys and over passes, visiting temples and meeting monks who kept the mountain's long history in their hearts, I came at last to the Sokul Temple with its thousand Buddhas and the infinite lamp that multiplied every flame into ten thousand, a marvel of both art and faith.

    The journey complete, I made my way homeward through rain and fair weather, crossing rivers, passing through towns and villages, until at last I returned to the capital, having traveled in mountains some four hundred eighty-five li, by water two hundred seventy-four li, and over level ground nine hundred thirty-seven li.

    So I record this journey in the fourth month of the year of the tiger, on the twenty-first day.
